  <article>
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm Alex. 26. First-gen Guatemalan-American. Virginia.
      No CS degree — I learned to build by building.
    </p>

    <p>
      I spent five years at a credit union, got promoted four times,
      and started noticing the same thing across every system I touched:
      the way a system describes you changes how you get treated —
      and eventually, how you see yourself. Labels that don't match
      the architecture underneath. Resumes that flatten a person into keywords.
      Models that compress you into a prediction and feed it back.
    </p>

    <p>
      So I started building. Software where you can see how the system
      sees you, own the record, and decide what stays.
    </p>

    <p>
      That shows up as a <a href="https://reframed.works">resume tool</a> that's live
      and making money. An <a href="/projects/forgeframe">open-source memory system</a>
      for AI agents. A <a href="https://guardian-labs.org">brain study</a> that showed
      psychiatric diagnosis doesn't predict neural architecture. A
      <a href="/projects/guardian">desktop app</a> that keeps your data on your machine.
      Different shapes, same question.
    </p>

    <p>
      During the day I'm a Senior Process Manager at Capital One — regulatory operations,
      failure analysis, monitoring infrastructure for a $600M+ file exchange network.
      Nights and weekends: everything else on this site.
    </p>

    <p>
      This site is homecooked — Astro, vanilla JS, WebGL shaders, no frameworks.
      If you opened the console, you already know the voice.
    </p>

